RXQPSMMN,"Tucatinib, Trastuzumab, and Capecitabine for HER2-Positive Metastatic Breast Cancer",Giuseppe Curigliano; Lisa A. Carey; Eric P. Winer; Sara A. Hurvitz; Mafalda Oliveira; Sibylle Loibl; Sherene Loi; Rashmi K. Murthy; Alicia Okines; Elisavet Paplomata; Erika Hamilton; Nancy U. Lin; Virginia Borges; Vandana Abramson; Carey Anders; Philippe L. Bedard; Erik Jakobsen; Thomas Bachelot; Shlomit S. Shachar; Volkmar Müller; Sofia Braga; Francois P. Duhoux; Richard Greil; David Cameron; Karen Gelmon; Gabriel Hortobagyi; Ian Krop; Mark Pegram; Dennis Slamon; M. Corinna Palanca-Wessels; Luke Walker; Wentao Feng,2020,New England Journal of Medicine,10.1056/NEJMoa1914609,https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1914609,"In women with HER2-positive metastatic breast cancer who had previously received HER2-targeted therapy, tucatinib, a new selective inhibitor of the HER2 tyrosine kinase, was added to trastuzumab and capecitabine and compared with trastuzumab and capecitabine plus placebo. Progression-free survival at 1 year was 33% with tucatinib and 12% with placebo.",🗝,strong_positive,0,0,1,HER2-positive Breast Cancer,False,243,must_read,high,5.0,must_read,,,,,,0.8750,must_read,holdout,0.8421,must_read,holdout,0.4915,should_read,holdout,,,,dont_read,0.9600,"The paper reports a clinical drug trial for breast cancer and contains no mention of multiagent systems, AI, or software pipelines, which are the researcher’s primary interests."
